# Phase 3: Linux Permissions & Ownership

## 1. File Permissions Overview
- Linux permissions: `r` (read), `w` (write), `x` (execute)
- Owner, Group, Others
- View permissions: `ls -l`

## 2. Changing Permissions
- `chmod 644 file.txt` → owner read/write, group/others read
- `chmod 755 script.sh` → owner read/write/execute, others read/execute

## 3. Changing Ownership
- `chown user file.txt` → change owner
- `chown user:group file.txt` → change owner and group

## 4. Special Permissions
- `chmod +x file` → make executable
- `chmod u+s file` → setuid
- `chmod g+s dir` → setgid

## 5. Directory Permissions
- `r` → list files
- `w` → create/delete files
- `x` → access files in dir
## Permission Denied Errors

When running commands like `du` on system directories such as `/var`,
permission denied errors appear because many folders are owned by root.

To view full contents:

    sudo du -sh /var/*

Linux restricts access for security reasons.
